<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900417-0021</DOCNO><DOCID>900417-0021.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   The National Geographic's   Editor Abruptly Replaced</HL><DATE>04/17/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><CO>   WNEWS</CO><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)</IN><LP>   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The editor of National Geographicmagazine was replaced suddenly yesterday, and neither he northe society that publishes the magazine was saying whether hewas fired.   &quot;I just don't know the circumstances well enough to dealwith it,&quot; said Wilbur E. Garrett, 59 years old, who had beeneditor since 1980.</LP><TEXT>   He added that there had been some &quot;personality conflicts&quot;and some differences of opinion at the magazine, but hewouldn't elaborate on the circumstances of his abruptdeparture.   Mr. Garrett was succeeded by William T.E. Graves, 63, whohas been a senior member of the magazine's editorial stafffor 12 years.   Mr. Graves becomes the eighth editor in the 102-yearhistory of the publication that has explored the world andthe creatures that inhabit it. The magazine is sent to the 10million members of the National Geographic Society.   Robert Sims, a spokesman for the society, said Mr.Garrett's departure and Mr. Graves's promotion take effectimmediately.</TEXT></DOC>